Size. Known adult size about 
<quantity id="2E379B383F0CFF9BFE07F8AFFDA7F8A2" box="[486,583,1833,1859]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="9.0" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" unit="cm" value="9.5" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="9.0">9–10 cm</quantity>
total length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F0CFF98FF26F8CBFD56FD2F" lastPageId="58" lastPageNumber="59" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F0CFF9BFF26F8CBFD79F84E" blockId="57.[151,1437,1833,2041]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Morphology. D VI + I,13–14; A I,12–13; P 19–20. Medium-sized goby with moderately long body, large head, short snout. Caudal peduncle deep, but lower than body. Dorsal fins of similar height, the first dorsal fin with more or less rounded edge and no elongated spines.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F0CFF9BFF26F83FFD8EF816" blockId="57.[151,1437,1833,2041]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
Caudal fin rounded. Scales small, visible on body and usually on predorsal area as dense pattern. Predorsal area and nape scaled (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F0CFF9BFEB6F85BFD82F816" author="Kovacic, M. &amp; Sanda, R." box="[343,610,2012,2041]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="1104 - 1124" refId="ref58613" refString="Kovacic, M. &amp; Sanda, R. (2016) A new species of Gobius (Perciformes: Gobiidae) from the Mediterranean Sea and the redescription of Gobius bucchichi. Journal of Fish Biology, 88, 1104 - 1124. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / jfb. 12883" type="journal article" year="2016">Kovačić &amp; Šanda 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F0FFF98FF26FF11FE25FE14" blockId="58.[151,1437,150,719]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
Live coloration. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F0FFF98FE62FF11FEDCFF34" bold="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Body uniformly pale gray, greenish gray or light brown, covered with longitudinal lines of brown dots</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F0FFF98FEAAFF3DFE55FF34" box="[331,437,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,1115,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-43@35.[190,1397,1115,1920]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 37. A) Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius incognitus. B) Upper lip with brown marks in addition to the dot on the corner of the mouth; upper half of the eye with separate brown dots or radiating stripes without longitudinal curved mark. Photos by S.V. Bogorodsky, Turkey, Aegean Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601683" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601683/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 37A</figureCitation>
). The dots are broadest, darkest and most numerous along the lateral midline, where they coalesce in 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F0FFF98FEC0FF58FB8CFF18" bold="true" box="[289,1132,222,249]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">well-aligned midlateral dashes or blotches separated by white spaces</emphasis>
. Eyes with a conspicuous horizontal stripe through the center, 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F0FFF98FDAFFE85FDF3FEA0" bold="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">upper iris with separate brown dots or radiating stripes without a longitudinal mark uniting them</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F0FFF98FDC3FEA1FD65FEA3" box="[546,645,295,322]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,1115,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-43@35.[190,1397,1115,1920]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 37. A) Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius incognitus. B) Upper lip with brown marks in addition to the dot on the corner of the mouth; upper half of the eye with separate brown dots or radiating stripes without longitudinal curved mark. Photos by S.V. Bogorodsky, Turkey, Aegean Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601683" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601683/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 37b</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F0FFF98FD78FEA1FCEDFE84" bold="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">V-shaped line in the center of the snout. Three longitudinal rows of dots recognizable on cheek or in irregular pattern</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F0FFF98FCFCFECDFC60FE87" box="[797,896,331,358]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1895]" captionTargetId="figure-18@33.[151,1436,181,1895]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 33. The mouth unmarked at corner in A) G. bucchichi and B) H. ingressus. Dark dot on the corner of the mouth in C) G. auratus, D) G. incognitus, E) G. xanthocephalus and F) G. fallax. Area marked with hollow circle. Photos by R. Svensen (A), S. Engin (B), M. Kovačić (C, D, F), and P. Louisy (E). C and F photographed in a tank." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601673" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601673/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 33d</figureCitation>
); the median row more or less regularly crosses the center of the cheek, parallel to the lower row. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F0FFF98FD59FEE9FA97FE68" bold="true" box="[696,1399,366,393]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">There is a well-defined dark dot at posterior angle of mouth</emphasis>
, so the lower row begins with an isolated dot at the corner of the mouth, usually followed by 2 short horizontal dashes. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F0FFF98FF76FE31FBA9FE30" bold="true" box="[151,1097,438,465]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Upper lip with brown marks in addition to the dot on the corner of the mouth</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F0FFF98FBB8FE31FB5BFE33" box="[1113,1211,439,466]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,1115,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-43@35.[190,1397,1115,1920]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 37. A) Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius incognitus. B) Upper lip with brown marks in addition to the dot on the corner of the mouth; upper half of the eye with separate brown dots or radiating stripes without longitudinal curved mark. Photos by S.V. Bogorodsky, Turkey, Aegean Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601683" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601683/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 37b</figureCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F0FFF98FB33FE31FF33FE14" author="Kovacic, M. &amp; Sanda, R." pageId="58" pageNumber="59" pagination="1104 - 1124" refId="ref58613" refString="Kovacic, M. &amp; Sanda, R. (2016) A new species of Gobius (Perciformes: Gobiidae) from the Mediterranean Sea and the redescription of Gobius bucchichi. Journal of Fish Biology, 88, 1104 - 1124. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / jfb. 12883" type="journal article" year="2016">Kovačić &amp; Šanda 2016</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F0FFF98FF3FFE5DFE5AFE14" author="Renoult, J. P. &amp; Pillon, R. &amp; Kovacic, M. &amp; Louisy, P." box="[222,442,475,501]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" refId="ref63723" refString="Renoult, J. P., Pillon, R., Kovacic, M. &amp; Louisy, P. (2022) Frontiers in Fishwatching Series - Gobies of North-eastern Atlantic and the Mediterranean: Gobius and Thorogobius. Les cahiers de la fondation Biotope. [in press]" type="book" year="2022">
Renoult 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F0FFF98FEDFFE5DFE8FFE14" box="[318,367,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">et al</emphasis>
. 2022
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F0FFF98FF26FE79FD5BFDF8" blockId="58.[151,1437,150,719]" box="[199,699,511,537]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F0FFF98FE9EFE79FDA4FDF8" authorityName="Steindachner" authorityYear="1870" box="[383,580,511,537]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Gobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bucchichi">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F0FFF98FE9EFE79FDA4FDF8" box="[383,580,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Gobius bucchichi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F0FFF98FDB3FE79FD54FDF8" authorityName="Sarato" authorityYear="1889" box="[594,692,511,537]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Gobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fallax">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F0FFF98FDB3FE79FD86FDF8" box="[594,614,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">G</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F0FFF98FD95FE79FD54FDF8" box="[628,692,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">fallax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F0FFF98FF26FDA5FD84FD64" blockId="58.[151,1437,150,719]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
Habitat. Infralittoral species, known from 
<quantity id="2E379B383F0FFF98FD43FDA4FCECFDDC" box="[674,780,546,573]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.25" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" unit="m" value="6.25" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="0.5">0.5–12 m</quantity>
depth mostly on shallow and sub-horizontal bottoms with sand and stones or rocks (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F0FFF98FE21FDC1FD30FD83" author="Kovacic, M. &amp; Sanda, R." box="[448,720,583,611]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" pagination="1104 - 1124" refId="ref58613" refString="Kovacic, M. &amp; Sanda, R. (2016) A new species of Gobius (Perciformes: Gobiidae) from the Mediterranean Sea and the redescription of Gobius bucchichi. Journal of Fish Biology, 88, 1104 - 1124. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / jfb. 12883" type="journal article" year="2016">Kovačić &amp; Šanda 2016</bibRefCitation>
). At low depths it is typically associated with the sea anemone 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F0FFF98FF76FDEDFD80FD64" authority="(Tiralongo et al. 2020)" baseAuthorityName="Tiralongo" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[151,608,619,645]" class="Anthozoa" family="Actiniidae" genus="Anemonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="viridis">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F0FFF98FF76FDEDFEB8FD64" box="[151,344,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Anemonia viridis</emphasis>
(Tiralongo 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F0FFF98FE3DFDEDFDEDFD64" box="[476,525,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">et al</emphasis>
. 2020)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F0FFF98FF26FD09FD56FD2F" blockId="58.[151,1437,150,719]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
Geographic distribution. Mediterranean. Confirmed presence from the northwestern Mediterranean to the Aegean Sea and 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F0FFF98FEB2FD35FE71FD2C" box="[339,401,691,717]" name="Israel" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Israel</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F0FFF98FE7EFD35FD4BFD2F" author="Kovacic, M. &amp; Sanda, R." box="[415,683,691,719]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" pagination="1104 - 1124" refId="ref58613" refString="Kovacic, M. &amp; Sanda, R. (2016) A new species of Gobius (Perciformes: Gobiidae) from the Mediterranean Sea and the redescription of Gobius bucchichi. Journal of Fish Biology, 88, 1104 - 1124. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / jfb. 12883" type="journal article" year="2016">Kovačić &amp; Šanda 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
